Each memory access is conceptually decoupled into a "read" operation
and a "write" operation, where the write simply increments the counter.
The reads are represented by set R and the writes are represented
by set W. R and W are consist of tuples much like the initialize set I,
but they are of size s (sparsity, i.e. number of lookups).
One element gets added to R and W each per lookup
The final memory state, after all lookups (reads/writes) are performed.
Note that the addresses and values remain the same, only the counters
The final memory state can be represented by the set F.
Each element is a tuple describing a memory slot.
A counter value of 5 means that this
memory slot was accessed 5 times over
the course of all the lookups.
The memory-checking invariant is the following:
I U W = R U F
Intuitively, every memory tuple that was read must have been written at some point.
The "init" tuples are basically a special case of "write",
and the "final" tuples are a special case of "read".
